public String slanted_transposition_cipher(String encodedText, int rows) {
    if(rows == 1)
        return encodedText;

    int n = encodedText.length();
    int cols = (n + rows - 2) / (rows - 1);
    int pos = 0;
    char[][] matrix = new char[rows][cols];
    for(int k = 0; k < cols; ++k) {
        for(int i = 0; i < rows; ++i) {
            if(k % 2 == 0 || i != 0) {
                matrix[i][k] = encodedText.charAt(pos++);
            }
        }
    }
    StringBuilder originalText = new StringBuilder();
    for(char[] row : matrix) {
        for (char c : row) {
            originalText.append(c);
        }
    }
    return originalText.toString();
}
```

    The algorithm works as follows:
1. If there's only 1 row, the original text is the same as the encoded text.
2. Given the length of the encoded text, calculate the number of columns while ensuring the rightmost column is filled completely. This is calculated using the formula: `(n + rows - 2) / (rows - 1)`.
3. Create a matrix with the given number of rows and calculated number of columns.
4. Fill in the matrix by iterating through each row and column. If the current column is even or the current row is not the first row, add the current character of the encodedText at the current matrix position.
5. Iterate through the matrix and append each character to a new string, forming the original text.
